  "footnotes": [
    "Botai culture (c.3500 BCE): the earliest archaeological evidence of horse domestication in the world; found in north-central Kazakhstan; bit-wear on horse teeth and penning structures confirm domestic horses 1,000 years before previously thought",
    "Sintashta culture (c.2100–1800 BCE): the oldest known war chariots (spoked wheel, two-horse drawn) were found at Sintashta sites in the southern Ural region; this culture is the likely ancestor of the Proto-Indo-Iranian language branch — both Vedic Sanskrit and Avestan are descended from it",
    "Yueban Kingdom (c.350–490 CE): a remnant Xiongnu state that survived in the Aral Sea region after the Hunnic westward migration; it was eventually absorbed by the Hephthalites and represents the last flicker of Xiongnu state organization",
    "Pechenegs (c.860–900): a Turkic-speaking confederation that originated in the eastern steppe (Ural/Caspian region) before being pushed westward by Oghuz pressure; they became a major power on the Pontic steppe and defeated the Kievan Rus repeatedly",
    "Alash Autonomy (1917–1920): the short-lived Kazakh national government formed during the Russian Revolution; led by Kazakh intellectuals (Bokeikhanov, Baitursynov, Dulatov), it represented the first modern Kazakh state; it was suppressed by the Bolsheviks in 1920 but left a lasting legacy in Kazakh national consciousness",
    "Soviet delimitation: the division between Kyrgyz-Kazakh ASSR (later separate Kazakh and Kyrgyz SSRs) and the Turkestan ASSR (covering Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, southern Kazakhstan) reflected Stalin's divide-and-rule national policy; the Kazakh SSR was formally established in 1936"
  ]
}
